            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Linh Miller\u2019s story began not in the fog of San Francisco, but in the chaos of 1975 Saigon. She was an infant when her parents fled, carrying little more than their baby daughter and a desperate hope for safety. They eventually settled in San Francisco\u2019s Richmond District, where the cool, gray climate was a world away from the home they\u2019d lost. Her parents worked tirelessly in restaurants and cleaning jobs, instilling in Linh a formidable work ethic. While her friends dreamed of college, Linh was pragmatic; she saw the path to independence through tangible skills. After high school, she enrolled in cosmetology school, quickly discovering a talent for the meticulous art of nail design.\n\nHer career began at a small salon on Clement Street. It was there she met Mark Miller, a kind, lanky graphic designer who came in to buy a gift certificate for his mother. Their romance was a gentle merging of worlds. He encouraged her dream of owning her own place, helping her create a business plan and co-signing the initial loan. In her early thirties, she opened \"Inner Sunset Nails.\"\n\nThe true turning point came a decade ago with Mark\u2019s sudden death from a heart attack. The grief was a tidal wave, but the salon became her anchor. It was not just a business; it was her and Mark\u2019s legacy. She poured her energy into it, transforming it into a neighborhood sanctuary where clients became confidantes. Her staff are like a second family, a mix of Vietnamese aunties and younger, trend-savvy technicians.\n\nNow 49, Linh\u2019s life is a steady rhythm. Her 0.8-mile walk from her small apartment to the salon is a daily meditation. She knows the shopkeepers, the morning dog-walkers, the unique scent of eucalyptus and fog. Her income is comfortable but hard-won, every dollar reinvested into the business or saved for her son, Alex, now a sophomore at UC Davis. Her greatest hope is to see him graduate without debt. She dreams not of riches, but of quiet contentment: a thriving salon, a secure future for her son, and perhaps one day, traveling to a Vietnam she can\u2019t remember but feels etched into her soul."
        },
