            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers her father\u2019s hands, not his face from that time. They were chapped and raw from dishwater and cleaning chemicals, but they were always gentle when they touched her cheek. He\u2019d come home smelling of bleach and exhaustion, a scent she came to associate with survival. In the roughness of his palms, Linh understood that a life was not dreamed, but built. She learned early that salvation lay in skilled, tireless hands, a lesson that led her away from books and toward the precision of her own craft. This was in her childhood, a constant memory from the 1980s.\n\n***\n\n2.\nThe night they planned the salon, their small apartment was filled with the glow of Mark\u2019s laptop and the scent of lukewarm takeout. Spreadsheets and swatches covered the coffee table. She was terrified, but Mark traced the logo he\u2019d designed\u2014a stylized lotus\u2014and his belief was so steady it became her own. He saw a successful business owner in her before she could see it herself. That night, her dream stopped being a fantasy and became a tangible plan, their shared secret against the world. This was in her late twenties, the year before opening the salon.\n\n***\n\n3.\nTen days after Mark\u2019s funeral, she walked back into the salon. The familiar chemical tang of acetone and the low hum of the UV lamps felt both alien and anchoring. Everything was exactly as he\u2019d last seen it. Her throat closed up, but then one of the aunties quietly refilled the acetone jars and a longtime client simply squeezed her arm. The grief was a silent ocean inside her, but the salon was a life raft. It was in that moment she knew the business had to survive. It was all she had left of him.\n\n***\n\n4.\nDropping Alex off at his UC Davis dorm was the hardest walk of her life. After the last hug, she turned away, trying not to let him see her cry. The two-hour drive back to San Francisco felt endless and empty. The silence in the car was a physical weight. Yet, beneath the ache was a fierce, sharp pride. This was it. This was the point of the endless hours, the scrimping, the sacrifice. It was the loneliest and most triumphant she had ever felt, watching their shared dream for their son finally begin. This was two years ago.\n\n***\n\n5.\nJust last week, on her morning walk down 9th Avenue, she saw her reflection in the window of the bakery. A woman, nearly 50, with faint lines of worry and laughter around her eyes, her posture straight from years of leaning over nail tables. For a fleeting second, she didn\u2019t see the refugee, the widow, or the struggling mother. She saw the owner of Inner Sunset Nails, a woman who knew her neighbors by name. A quiet contentment settled over her. This was not the life she had lost, but the one she had built."
